<p>This code probably isn’t driving the robot the way you think it should.</p>
<ul>
<li>Robot forward is positive X</li>
<li>Robot left is positive Y</li>
<li>Robot rotation is counter-clockwise positive</li>
</ul>
<p><div class="lightbox-wrapper"><a class="lightbox" href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/2/f/2f7a1cda3aea22b05e5440b6cd37e44567157c25.png" data-download-href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/2f7a1cda3aea22b05e5440b6cd37e44567157c25" title="image"><img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/2/f/2f7a1cda3aea22b05e5440b6cd37e44567157c25_2_690x430.png" alt="image" data-base62-sha1="6M0478YuKpbEtLR84wlgQsfrplj" width="690" height="430" srcset="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/2/f/2f7a1cda3aea22b05e5440b6cd37e44567157c25_2_690x430.png, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/2/f/2f7a1cda3aea22b05e5440b6cd37e44567157c25_2_1035x645.png 1.5x, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/2/f/2f7a1cda3aea22b05e5440b6cd37e44567157c25.png 2x" data-dominant-color="F7F8F7"><div class="meta"><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#far-image"></use></svg><span class="filename">image</span><span class="informations">1078×673 35.6 KB</span><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#discourse-expand"></use></svg></div></a></div></p>
<p>Joysticks, on the other hand, are:</p>
<ul>
<li>backwards is positive Y</li>
<li>right is positive X</li>
</ul>
<p>Joystick values are rotation around the axis:<br>
<div class="lightbox-wrapper"><a class="lightbox" href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/f/8/f8bf0056cc64e5df5a37a24ced21e09d722a68fe.jpeg" data-download-href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/f8bf0056cc64e5df5a37a24ced21e09d722a68fe" title="image"><img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/f/8/f8bf0056cc64e5df5a37a24ced21e09d722a68fe_2_540x500.jpeg" alt="image" data-base62-sha1="zuvD81XZPQWeYnfgR0GL8WFxjoq" width="540" height="500" srcset="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/f/8/f8bf0056cc64e5df5a37a24ced21e09d722a68fe_2_540x500.jpeg, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/f/8/f8bf0056cc64e5df5a37a24ced21e09d722a68fe_2_810x750.jpeg 1.5x, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/f/8/f8bf0056cc64e5df5a37a24ced21e09d722a68fe.jpeg 2x" data-dominant-color="F3F3F3"><div class="meta"><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#far-image"></use></svg><span class="filename">image</span><span class="informations">1069×988 68.5 KB</span><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#discourse-expand"></use></svg></div></a></div></p>
<p>So, you need to invert the values from the joystick. I also recommend matching the variable names (you have x named y, and y named x)</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">double x = -controller.getLeftY();
double y = -controller.getLeftX();
double turn = -controller.getRightX();
drive.driveCartesian(x, y, turn);
</code></pre>","post_number":6,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-01-23T06:04:41.252Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":97,"readers_count":96,"score":24.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":451565,"topic_slug":"mecanumdrive-unintended-behavior","display_username":"Andy Gasser","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/f/8/f8bf0056cc64e5df5a37a24ced21e09d722a68fe.jpeg","internal":true,"reflection":false,"clicks":0},{"url":"https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/2/f/2f7a1cda3aea22b05e5440b6cd37e44567157c25.png","internal":true,"reflection":false,"clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":44380,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"7028 - Java Programming Mentor"},"post_url":"/t/mecanumdrive-unintended-behavior/451565/6","custom_user_title":"7028 - Java Programming Mentor","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3292053,"name":"Andy Gasser","username":"gdefender","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/gdefender/{size}/168507_2.png","created_at":"2024-01-23T06:03:02.090Z","cooked":"<p>Building in the problem above, you probably have your motors inverted incorrectly. With your code, when you push forward on the controller, the robot should move backwards. When you press to the right, the robot should move left.</p>
<p>The fact that the robot <em>appears</em> to moving the right way is probably an indication that your motors are not inverted correctly. Positive output should make the motors drive forward. Incorrect inversion would appear to work for forward and backward, but would not work for rotation.</p>","post_number":7,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-01-23T06:03:02.090Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":6,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":79,"readers_count":78,"score":20.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":451565,"topic_slug":"mecanumdrive-unintended-behavior","display_username":"Andy Gasser","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":44380,"username":"gdefender","name":"Andy Gasser","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/gdefender/{size}/168507_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":44380,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"7028 - Java Programming Mentor"},"post_url":"/t/mecanumdrive-unintended-behavior/451565/7","custom_user_title":"7028 - Java Programming Mentor","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3292423,"name":"Kaiden McMartin","username":"trip-kun","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/t/779978/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-01-23T19:12:05.608Z","cooked":"<p>I’m using an Xbox Controller, not a large joystick. I’m aware of the left/right being backwards. Although front/back is not (and is driving as expected front and back).</p>
<p>I’ve looked at the inversion states of the motors, and they are as expected to have the chassis move in the 4 directions correctly (front wheels inverted, rear wheels normal).</p>
<p>As of right now:</p>
<p>Positive input from left stick Y - &gt; X input for Cartesian - &gt; forward movement, and vice versa<br>
Positive input from left stick X - &gt; Y input for Cartesian - &gt; leftwards movement (can use - for expected drive behavior.<br>
Positive input from right stick X - &gt; turn input for Cartesian - &gt; The diagrammed unintended behavior</p>","post_number":8,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-01-23T19:12:05.608Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":7,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":61,"readers_count":60,"score":17.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":451565,"topic_slug":"mecanumdrive-unintended-behavior","display_username":"Kaiden McMartin","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":44380,"username":"gdefender","name":"Andy Gasser","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/gdefender/{size}/168507_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":63503,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/mecanumdrive-unintended-behavior/451565/8","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3292436,"name":"Kaiden McMartin","username":"trip-kun","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/t/779978/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-01-23T19:26:52.564Z","cooked":"<p>I have triple checked the <span class="abbreviation">CAN<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Controller Area Network"></template></span> ids and sparks on the bot.<br>
For clarity,<br>
CanID 1 front left<br>
2 back left<br>
3 back right<br>
4 front right</p>
<p>Swapping front left and back right in the code appears to produce a fix. The motors are in a different order than the Mecanum Drive constructor asks for.</p>
<p>I’ll take the fix either way, however, this is odd behavior from MecanumDrive</p>","post_number":9,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-01-23T19:26:52.564Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":50,"readers_count":49,"score":15.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":451565,"topic_slug":"mecanumdrive-unintended-behavior","display_username":"Kaiden McMartin","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":19820,"username":"ArchdukeTim","name":"Tim Winters","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/archduketim/{size}/256125_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":63503,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/mecanumdrive-unintended-behavior/451565/9","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3292490,"name":"Andy Gasser","username":"gdefender","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/gdefender/{size}/168507_2.png","created_at":"2024-01-23T20:05:21.001Z","cooked":"<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="trip-kun" data-post="8" data-topic="451565">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/t/779978/48.png" class="avatar"> trip-kun:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>Xbox Controller, not a large joystick</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>The axes are the same on an XBox controller as they are on a large joystick.</p>
<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="trip-kun" data-post="8" data-topic="451565">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/t/779978/48.png" class="avatar"> trip-kun:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>front wheels inverted, rear wheels normal</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>This is unusual, but it depends on your robot build. Usually the right side is inverted, and the left side is not.<br>
Are you 100% sure that positive output on the motor results in forward motion of the wheel?</p>
<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="trip-kun" data-post="8" data-topic="451565">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/t/779978/48.png" class="avatar"> trip-kun:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>Positive input from left stick Y - &gt; X input for Cartesian - &gt; forward movement, and vice versa</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>This is wrong, unless you want to push the controller stick toward you to drive the robot forward. Positive input from the left Y is pulling the stick toward you. Pushing it away from you is negative.</p>
<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="trip-kun" data-post="8" data-topic="451565">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/t/779978/48.png" class="avatar"> trip-kun:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>Positive input from left stick X - &gt; Y input for Cartesian - &gt; leftwards movement (can use - for expected drive behavior.</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>I think you’re saying you have to invert the input from the left stick, that would be correct. Pushing the left stick to the right will result in <em>postive</em> X input, so it needs to be inverted.</p>
<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="trip-kun" data-post="8" data-topic="451565">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/t/779978/48.png" class="avatar"> trip-kun:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>Positive input from right stick X - &gt; turn input for Cartesian - &gt; The diagrammed unintended behavior</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>Positive input from the right stick is pushing the stick to the right. It needs to be inverted because robot rotation is CCW (left) positive.</p>
<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="trip-kun" data-post="9" data-topic="451565">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/t/779978/48.png" class="avatar"> trip-kun:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>Swapping front left and back right in the code appears to produce a fix. The motors are in a different order than the Mecanum Drive constructor asks for.</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>This is because you’re telling the <code>MecanumDrive</code> class you want to move in a different direction than you intend. It’s up to you if you want to leave your workaround and move forward, but I highly recommend getting it fixed properly. If you want to implement odometry, pose estimation, or path planning for autonomous, you’ll need to keep implementing workarounds throughout the code if you don’t use the correct coordinate system.</p>
<p>It seems like you don’t believe I am correct, so I’ll include some references. You can also look in <a href="https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/basic-programming/joystick.html#driver-station-joysticks" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">Driver Station</a> while you move the sticks around, and confirm the behavior with your robot’s motors.</p>
<ul>
<li>From the <a href="https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/hardware-apis/motors/wpi-drive-classes.html#axis-conventions" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">Axis Conventions</a> documentation</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p>The drive classes use the NWU axes convention… The positive X axis points ahead, the positive Y axis points left, and the positive Z axis points up…</p>
<p>Joysticks follow NED (North-East-Down) convention, where the positive X axis points ahead, the positive Y axis points right, and the positive Z axis points down. However, it’s important to note that axes values are rotations around the respective axes, not translations. When viewed with each axis pointing toward you, CCW is a positive value and CW is a negative value. Pushing forward on the joystick is a CW rotation around the Y axis, so you get a negative value. Pushing to the right is a CCW rotation around the X axis, so you get a positive value.</p>
</blockquote>
<ul>
<li>From the <a href="https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/hardware-apis/motors/wpi-drive-classes.html#mecanum-drive-modes" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">mecanum drive modes</a> example code:</li>
</ul>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">m_robotDrive.driveCartesian(-m_stick.getY(), -m_stick.getX(), -m_stick.getZ());
</code></pre>
<ul>
<li>From the <a href="https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/basic-programming/joystick.html#joystick-class" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">WPILib joystick documentation</a>.</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p>Important</p>
<p>Forward on joysticks is the negative direction. Teams often negate the values when reading joystick axes to account for this.</p>
</blockquote>","post_number":10,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-01-23T20:05:21.001Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":8,"quote_count":2,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":43,"readers_count":42,"score":73.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":451565,"topic_slug":"mecanumdrive-unintended-behavior","display_username":"Andy Gasser","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/hardware-apis/motors/wpi-drive-classes.html#axis-conventions","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Using the WPILib Classes to Drive your Robot — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation","clicks":2},{"url":"https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/basic-programming/joystick.html#driver-station-joysticks","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Joysticks — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation","clicks":0},{"url":"https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/hardware-apis/motors/wpi-drive-classes.html#mecanum-drive-modes","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Using the WPILib Classes to Drive your Robot — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation","clicks":0},{"url":"https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/basic-programming/joystick.html#joystick-class","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Joysticks — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation","clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":2}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":44380,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"7028 - Java Programming Mentor"},"post_url":"/t/mecanumdrive-unintended-behavior/451565/10","custom_